{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Duane Alexander | honorific_suffix = | image = duane alexander.jpg | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above --> | birth_date = August 11, 1940 | birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = American | education = Johns Hopkins University (MD) | alma_mater = | occupation = American physician | years_active = *Director of the [[National Institute of Child Health and Human Development]] from 1986 through 2009 *Senior scientific adviser to the Director of the [[National Institutes of Health|NIH's]] Fogarty International Center from 2009 | era = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | spouse = Marianne Ellis | partner = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) --> | children = Keith and Kristin | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | footnotes = }}
'''Duane Alexander''' (born August 11, 1940 in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]])<ref>''Who's Who in America" 1986-1987 edition, p. 34</ref> is an American physician who was the director of the [[National Institute of Child Health and Human Development]] from 1986 through 2009. In 2009 he moved to the position of senior scientific advisor to the Director of the [[National Institutes of Health|NIH's]] Fogarty International Center.
Alexander married Marianne Ellis in 1963. They have two children, Keith and Kristin.
He received his MD from [[Johns Hopkins]].
